Problem Definition¶

  • For Thera bank Customers with credit cards services is one of their important product which generate continuous revenue. The bank do not want customers to leave from this service else bank would loss money (revenue)

  • As a Data scientist at Thera bank, I would need to come up with a classification model that will help the bank improve its services so that customers do not renounce their credit cards

Insight after reading the backround and context:¶

  • My understanding after reading data dictionary: Months_Inactive_12_mon, Contacts_Count_12_mon, Total_Revolving_Ba, either Total_Trans_Amt or Total_Trans_ct, Avg_Utilization_Ratio are important features to look into. I'm assuming that these features would play key role to understand the pattern of customers credit card usage.

  • I have used feature engineering techniques such as one hot encoding, handling missing values where they should not be, outlier detection.

  • I built 18 models and hypertuned the best three. Finally I picked the top model one which one gave better recall and precision on validation data.

  • I applied this on to test data.

  • As a final step I built pipeline and offered my conclusions and recommendations.

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

Few details about categorical variables¶

  • Attrition_Flag: Attrition_Flag is a dependent class distribution, the target variable is imbalanced.
  • The dataset have 84% customers are existing on and only 16% are attrited customers. The goal is not to increase the attrited customer count.
  • Gender: Gender has almost equal representation but females are leading
  • Education-level: Gradutes are leading followed by highschool and college. There are about 1500 are uneducated. May be this is the reason why certain customers are not using CC actively due to their income is not stable.
  • Income_Category: About 3500 are having less than 40K 1/3 of customers are in this bucket. Abc also representing around 1000, not sure if the data is corrupted or for certain customers it is not known. I would create a bucket called 'unknown' and leave then there than taking mean or mode value.
  • Card_Category- Almost Blue is far superior than other cards. Platinum and gold are almost negligible
  • Months_Inactive_12_mon: About 3500 are in 3 month category. There are about 1000 customers not using card more than 4 months. It may be better to call them individually and offer certain benefits to encourge these customers to be more active could certainly increases the revenue.

Summary of EDA¶

Data Description:¶

Target variable 'Attrition_Flag': About 84% are existing customers. 16% are Attrited customers.

There are missing values in the dataset like in Education_Level,Marital_Status.

Data Cleaning:¶

  • ID is a unique variable so it is dropped from the data.
  • All missing values will be treated after data split.
  • Credit_limit has 'abc' in about 1100 records. I marked them as 'un-known' since I do not know which income to put.It is normal that customers some times either do not have income, self-employed or dependents who own the card along with a partner.

Outliers¶

  • Found few outliers in different feature like Credit_limit, customer_age,Total_Revolving_balance, Total_Trans_Amt, - - Average_open_to_buy. Customers with Customer_age > 70 has 2 records. I felt it is okay to delete them. Rest of them I did not treat them becuase these represents market data.

Observations from EDA:¶

  • Most of the features are right-skewed except customer_age which is symmetrical.
  • Most of the ustomers credit limit is 4500.
  • Months_Inactive_12_mon & Contacts_Count_12_mon are almost having same type of data.
  • About Total Transaction amount is 3899 for 50 % means most of the credit limit amount is spending by these customers, these are very active ones.
  • Total_Trans_Ct & Total_Trans_Amt sharing simlar kind of data about cusotmers

Model evaluation criterion¶

I will be using Recall as a metric for my model performance because here company could face two type of losses 1) If cusotmers renouce their credit cards - Loss of money (revenue) , a direct loss. 2) If cusotomers hold the credit card and do not use it - it is also a loss but at least bank would get anual fee as s revenue, not a complete loss.

Which Loss is greater?¶

1) If cusotmers renouce their credit cards - Loss of money (revenue) , a direct loss.

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Negatives?¶

Company wants recall to be maximized i.e. we need to reduce the number of false negatives.

Model building - 6 models¶

In [49]:
models = []  # Empty list to store all the models

# Appending models into the list
models.append(("Bagging", BaggingClassifier(random_state=1)))
models.append(("Random forest", RandomForestClassifier(random_state=1)))
models.append(("GBM", GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=1)))
models.append(("Adaboost", AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=1)))
models.append(("Xgboost", XGBClassifier(random_state=1, eval_metric="logloss")))
models.append(("dtree", DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)))

results = []  # Empty list to store all model's CV scores
names = []  # Empty list to store name of the models
score = []
# loop through all models to get the mean cross validated score
print("\n" "Cross-Validation Performance:" "\n")
for name, model in models:
    scoring = "recall"
    kfold = StratifiedKFold(
        n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=1
    )  # Setting number of splits equal to 5
    cv_result = cross_val_score(
        estimator=model, X=X_train, y=y_train, scoring=scoring, cv=kfold
    )
    results.append(cv_result)
    names.append(name)
    print("{}: {}".format(name, cv_result.mean() * 100))

print("\n" "Validation Performance:" "\n")

for name, model in models:
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    scores = recall_score(y_val, model.predict(X_val))
    score.append(scores)
    print("{}: {}".format(name, scores))

# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [59]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Pipelines for productionizing the model¶

  • Since the final model is identified. It is time to build pipelines to put the model into production.

Column Transformer¶

The concept of pipelines is to standardize the model building, but the steps in a pipeline are applied to each and every variable. This is useful for heterogeneous or columnar data, to combine several feature extraction mechanisms or transformations into a single transformer. I'm going to create 2 different pipelines, one for numerical columns and one for categorical columns For numerical columns, I will do missing value imputation as pre-processing For categorical columns, I will do one hot encoding and missing value imputation as pre-processing

I'm going to doing missing value imputation for the whole data, so that if there is any missing value in the data in future that can be taken care of.

In [78]:
# creating a list of numerical variables
numerical_features = [
    "Customer_Age", 
    "Total_Trans_Ct", 
    "Credit_Limit", 
    "Total_Revolving_Bal",
    "Months_Inactive_12_mon",
    "Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1",
    "Contacts_Count_12_mon",
]

# creating a transformer for numerical variables, which will apply simple imputer on the numerical variables
numeric_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy="median"))])

# creating a list of categorical variables
categorical_features = [
   "Gender",
    "Education_Level",
    "Marital_Status",
    "Income_Category",
    "Card_Category",
    "Dependent_count",

]

# creating a transformer for categorical variables, which will first apply simple imputer and
# then do one hot encoding for categorical variables
categorical_transformer = Pipeline(
    steps=[
        ("imputer", SimpleImputer(strategy="most_frequent")),
        ("onehot", OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore")),
    ]
)

# handle_unknown = "ignore", allows model to handle any unknown category in the test data

# combining categorical transformer and numerical transformer using a column transformer

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ("num", numeric_transformer, numerical_features),
        ("cat", categorical_transformer, categorical_features),
    ],
    remainder="passthrough",
)
# remainder = "passthrough" has been used, it will allow variables that are present in original data
# but not in "numerical_columns" and "categorical_columns" to pass through the column transformer without any changes

Recommendations, Conclusions and Insights¶

  • The best test recall is ~89% but the test precision is very low which is around .37 This means that the model is moderately well at identifying who are not attried customers. Since recall is at high, it may be good model for the bank to try and stop losing revenue.
  • There may be still a chance to improve the model performance and then reduce both false negatives and false positives. But by considering all aspects this model would serve the better.
  • In my analysis that customers who are not actively using the credit card has high chances of moving away (become attrited customers). The bank should continuously find new ways like offering various incentives, 0% promotional offers, reducing certain fees like annual fees , balance transfer fees to compensate the risk thus retaining customers. This proves both total_transaction_amt and total_transaction_count.
  • Contact_count proved the same, the more active contact between bank and customers maintain a healthy relationship and build trust with the bank, this leads to stop not using card.
  • Total_Revolving balance proves the same - The existing customers are having about 1200 balance where as attrited customers having around 600. Means if the balance is low meanes customers not actively using the card and slowly moving away from using card. Bank should have some threshhold like 1000 or 800, if the customer is below this amount, should make an attempt to call them and see what you can do to use them more often.
